            "> Remembering Hiroshima </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/hiroshima-anniversary-nuclear-call.jpg" alt="The Atomic Bomb Dome in Hiroshima illuminated at night, with crowds gathered along the riverbank and colorful paper lanterns floating on the water during the anniversary of the Hiroshima bombing." href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i> Hiroshima’s bomb had a yield of 15 kilotons, which is 80 times less powerful than the modern US nuclear weapons. Credits: The Plunge Daily </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> On the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-9-aug-25-sotw-h1-1-80th-anniversary?source=website" target="_blank">80th anniversary</a> of the Hiroshima bombing, world leaders, survivors, and experts warn that the planet is edging closer to nuclear catastrophe than it has been in decades. At a memorial ceremony in Hiroshima, Japan’s PM, Shigeru Ishiba, called for renewed disarmament efforts, while Nihon Hidankyo (the organization of atomic bomb survivors from Hiroshima and Nagasaki) urged nuclear states to change their stance. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> The warning comes amid rising geopolitical tensions. <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-9-aug-25-sotw-h1-2-russia-and-the-us?source=website" target="_blank">Russia and the US</a> have exchanged nuclear threats over the Ukraine war, the US has struck <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-9-aug-25-sotw-h1-3-iranian-nuclear-facilities?source=website" target="_blank">Iranian nuclear facilities</a> to prevent weapons development, and <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-9-aug-25-sotw-h1-4-india-and-pakistan?source=website" target="_blank">India and Pakistan</a> clashed briefly over Kashmir in May. All nuclear-armed states are upgrading their arsenals. The US and Russia together hold about 90% of the world’s 12,000 nuclear weapons. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> On August 6, 1945, the US dropped the uranium bomb “Little Boy” on Hiroshima, killing more than 110,000 people instantly. Three days later, the plutonium bomb “Fat Man” hit Nagasaki, killing 40,000-70,000 more people. Many more victims later died from burns, injuries, radiation sickness, and cancer. Survivors, known as Hibakusha, to date face health problems and generational effects (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-9-aug-25-sotw-h1-5-hibakusha-testimonies?source=website" target="_blank">Hibakusha testimonies</a>). </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> These bombings remain the sole use of nuclear weapons in war so far. </p>
        </mj-text>
