        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">What is happening in Texas?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> Texas is at the center of a heated redistricting battle. Democratic lawmakers have fled the state to block the Republican-controlled Legislature from passing the updated congressional maps (district boundaries that determine how voters are grouped for electing members of Congress). Republicans say the current maps are unconstitutional and racially gerrymandered, justifying a redraw. Democrats, on the other hand, argue the proposed maps would create more Republican-leaning districts, potentially boosting GOP seats in Congress from 25 to 30, while reducing the influence of minority communities, many of whom vote Democratic.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The rules:</strong> Redistricting happens every 10 years after the US Census to reflect population changes. Gerrymandering occurs when these district lines are drawn to unfairly favor one political party or group. <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-9-aug-25-tbq-h1-11-political-gerrymandering?source=website" target="_blank">Political gerrymandering</a> (which limits the opposing party’s seats) is allowed, but <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-9-aug-25-tbq-h1-12-racial-gerrymandering?source=website" target="_blank">racial gerrymandering</a> (which can impact the voting power of a racial or ethnic group) is prohibited.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>How it works:</strong> The mechanics rely on two tactics - packing and cracking. Packing concentrates the opposition’s voters, or, in racial gerrymandering, voters of a certain race, into just a few districts. They secure those districts by huge margins, but their influence elsewhere is neutralized. Cracking, however, spreads those voters thinly across many districts, so they’re always narrowly outnumbered and their votes are diluted. In both cases, a party can turn an evenly split statewide vote into a lopsided seat advantage.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> In Texas, the question is whether Republicans are engaging in permissible partisan map-drawing or crossing the line into illegal racial gerrymandering by diluting the political power of minority voters (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-9-aug-25-tbq-h1-13-see-our-write-up?source=website" target="_blank">see our write-up</a>).</p>
        </mj-text>
